Currently AbstractIterator retains a reference to the last returned element even after this element can no longer be accessed through the iterator. This becomes an issue when an iterator is used to generate and return extremely large object graphs which may consume sizable portions of available memory.

With the code as it currently stands, when computeNext() is called the reference to the previous element is strongly referenced and thus not garbage collectable until computeNext() returns. If computeNext requires large memory allocations, these may not be possible without allowing the previous reference to be garbage collected.

This should be a small change.

Current code:

public final T next() {
&nbsp;&nbsp;if (!hasNext()) {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;throw new NoSuchElementException();
&nbsp;&nbsp;}
&nbsp;&nbsp;state = State.NOT_READY;
&nbsp;&nbsp;return next;
}

Proposed code:

public final T next() {
&nbsp;&nbsp;if (!hasNext()) {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;throw new NoSuchElementException();
&nbsp;&nbsp;}
&nbsp;&nbsp;state = State.NOT_READY;

&nbsp;&nbsp;T tmp = next;
&nbsp;&nbsp;next = null;
&nbsp;&nbsp;return tmp;
}

