A super-type of DiscreteDomain&lt;C> allows for defining domains that aren't necessarily discrete; this also generalizes a function of discrete domains; just so long as you have two values, you are able to get the distance between them as well as get values between them so long as they exist.

```
Domain<C extends Comparable> {

    * Computes at most a specified number of elements between the origin and limit.
    *
    * @param maxElements
    * possibly fewer if there aren't enough elements between origin and limit.
    * 
    * @param setFunction
    * consumes either naturalOrder or reverseOrder depending on
    * origin-to-limit comparison.
    *
    <A extends NavigableSet<C>> A between(
            C origin,
            BoundType originBoundType,
            C limit,
            BoundType limitBoundType,
            int maxElements,
            Function<up Comparator<C>, xt A> setFunction);

    Optional<C> between(C origin, BoundType originBoundType, C limit, BoundType limitBoundType);

    * @return
    * as double can either give some finite number or infinite
    * as long will cap at [Long.MIN_VALUE, Long.MAX_VALUE].
    [double|long] distance(C origin, C limit);

    boolean discretizes(C origin, C limit) = !Double.isInfinite(distance(origin, limit));
    boolean adjoins(C origin, C limit) = Math.abs(distance(origin, limit)) <= 1;
}

Domain<BigDecimal> bigDecimals = {

    A between(C origin, ...) {
        final A set = setFunction.apply(
                origin.compareTo(limit) <=0 ? naturalOrder() : reverseOrder());

        for (C each : linspace(origin,originBoundType,limit,limitBoundType,maxElements))
            set.add(each);
        return set;
    }

    // linspace similar to MATLAB, whereas between is a generalization of linspace,
    // increment/decrement, etc.

    Optional<C> between(C origin, ...) {
        return Optional.of(mean(origin,limit));
    }

    double distance(C origin, ...) {
        return origin.compareTo(limit) <= 0 ? POSITIVE_INFINITY : NEGATIVE_INFINITY;
    }

};
```

Utilizing an instance of Domain along with some NavigableMap may simplify precedence problems; i.e. placing elements between two keys:

```
final NavigableMap<Integer, Strength> map = ...
final Domain<Integer> domain = DiscreteDomain.integers();
final int origin = ...;
final int limit = ...;

static Optional<C> add(
        NavigableMap<? super C, ? super V> map,
        Domain<C> domain,
        C origin,
        C limit,
        V value) {

    final BoundType boundType = BoundType.OPEN;
    final Optional<C> optional = domain.between(origin, boundType, limit, boundType);
    if (optional.isPresent())
        map.put(optional.get(), value);
    return optional;
}
```

