Moving this out into the open in case anyone has opinions.

The proposal is to replace Multimaps.newXYZMultimap with a fluent MultimapBuilder sort of API.

Sample before:

&nbsp;&nbsp;ListMultimap&lt;String, String> multimap = Multimaps.newListMultimap(
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Maps.newTreeMap&lt;String, Collection&lt;String>>(),
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;new Supplier&lt;List&lt;String>>() {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@ï»¿Override public List&lt;String> get() {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;return Lists.newArrayList();
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;});

Sample after:

&nbsp;&nbsp;ListMultimap&lt;String, String> multimap = 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;MultimapBuilder.treeKeys().arrayListValues().build();

&nbsp;&nbsp;ListMultimap&lt;String, String> multimap = 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;MultimapBuilder.treeKeys(Comparator).arrayListValues().build();
&nbsp;&nbsp;// We can manage to avoid needing any explicit generics,
&nbsp;&nbsp;// using tricks like what CacheBuilder uses with a K0 and a V0.

We have this checked into the internal labs, where it has accumulated 23 external references since mid-May without any publicity.

The primary remaining point of contention, from my perspective, is naming in terms of implementation versus function: e.g. treeKeys() versus sortedKeys(), linkedHashSetValues() versus insertionOrderedSetValues().  
Personally, I'm pretty firmly on the side of implementation-oriented naming: I don't see it as very likely that we'll actually change the implementations from the vanilla JDK versions, and I see having familiar names with familiar performance characteristics and semantics as more important than fully general naming.

Opinions welcome.

